column21: "Even game"
column22: "{Notes based on Shukan Shogi
column23: 97-May-14.} P7g-7f P8c-8d G6i-7h G4a-3b S7i-6h P3c-3d B8h-7g P8d-8e S3i-3h S7a-7b P2g-2f B2bx7g+ S6hx7g { As in the 2nd game
column24: we again see Tanigawa's specialty
column25: ~the Kakugawari Opening. } S3a-4b P1g-1f P1c-1d P9g-9f S4b-3c P4g-4f S7b-8c { Habu chooses the Bogin
column26: varying decisively from Game 2. ~All 3 games of this match so far have featured gote playing ~for an early initiative (and eventually losing). } S3h-4g S8c-8d P6g-6f P9c-9d G4i-5h { 3. R6h could also be considered. Tanigawa plays flexibly
column27: ~preserving the option of either K6h or K4h} K5a-4b {Habu invested 2 hours on this
column29: 13..P9e 14. P9e S9e 15. L9e L9e ~16. P9g P9h 17. S8h S4d!? was unappealing due to 18. P3f S5e ~19. B7g
column30: hitting the lance on 9e and preparing P6e. } P3g-3f G6a-5b N2i-3g P7c-7d P2f-2e P7d-7e K5i-6h { Opting against 17. K4h
column31: Tanigawa moves the king towards the battlefield. Strong defense. } P6c-6d S4g-5f K4b-3a { Already gote's game is not easy. Other possibilities are 18... P4d 19. P4e or 18... B5d 19. S6g. } N3g-4e {Usually in this type of position
column32: the attack starts with P3e to prepare a future pawn drop at 3c. Perhaps Habu expected 19. P3e P4d 20. P4e P3e~21. P4d P3f
column33: which gives gote counterchances. } S3c-4d {19... S4b (threatening ...P4d) would be met by 20. P2d P2d 21. B5e B4d 22. R2d P2c 23. R3d. } P2e-2d P2cx2d R2hx2d P'2c R2d-2i B'3h R2i-2e { Better than the normal 23. R2f. The rook's horizontal influence limits gote's counterattack while supporting P3e. } P7ex7f S7gx7f B3h-4i+ S5f-4g +B4i-3i { The threat was 26. R2i. Sadly
column34: the horse never moves again. Sente's advantage is now clear. } P1f-1e P1dx1e P3f-3e P8e-8f { If 27... P3e
column35: the attack continues 28. P1c L1c 29. P2d P2d 30. R2d P2c 31. R3d } P3ex3d P'3f { If here 28... S7e 29. S7e P8g+ 30. P8c +P7h 31. K7h R7b 32. P7c R7c 33. P7d R8c 34. P8d R8b 35. S3c
column36: and the horse is still completely out of~play. By interjecting 28... P3f 29 S3f
column37: Habu hopes to later activate the horse by +B4i
column38: attacking the undefended gold at 5h. However... } S4gx3f S8d-7e P3d-3c+ { Completely ignoring gote's last counterattempt. Ironically
column39: the silver Habu has invited to 3f will now figure in the attack. } N2ax3c N4ex3c+ S7ex7f +N3cx3b K3ax3b P'3c S4dx3c { If instead 33... K3c 34. N7d! R7b [34... P8g+ 35 N8b+] 35. P3d K3b 36. S3e R7d 37. R2c+ K4a 38. B6c decides the issue. } R2ex2c+ {!!!} K3bx2c B'4a { A possible contination is 35... P3b 36. N3e K3d 37. G4e K2d 38. P2e K1c 39. B3b+ S*6g 40. G76g S6g+ 41. K6g N7e 42. K5f. Habu thought for~1 minute and resigned. A beautiful game by Tanigawa. }"

column12: "Comments in the game by Reijer Grimbergen & Shukan Shogi"
column20: "Even game"
column21: "{~ Furigoma decided that Tanigawa could start the match with black. A couple of~ years ago there was talk that Habu could even mesmerize the pawns thrown to~ decide black and white
column22: but lately he seemed to have lost that ability :-).~ ~} P7g-7f P3c-3d P2g-2f P4c-4d S3i-4h S3a-4b P5g-5f P5c-5d G4i-5h S7a-6b {~ It was expected that Habu would play ranging rook
column23: but Habu decided to play~ Yagura. It was a year and three months ago that Habu and Tanigawa last played~ the Yagura opening against each other.~ ~} S7i-6h G6a-5b P3g-3f G5b-4c G6i-7h G4a-3b K5i-6i K5a-4a P4g-4f P8c-8d P2f-2e S4b-3c S4h-4g P8d-8e S6h-7g B2b-3a N2i-3g P7c-7d P9g-9f N8a-7c P6g-6f {~ The sealed move. 31.S6f also seems possible
column24: but after P6d P5e P6e the silver~ has to retreat to 5g which is not something one would like to do.~ ~} P6c-6d G5h-6g S6b-6c B8h-7i B3a-4b B7i-6h K4a-3a K6i-7i K3a-2b P4f-4e {~ Tanigawa: 'If I allow white to attack first
column25: I have no faith in the position
column26: ~ so! I! pushed on'. Now the fight starts.~ ~} P4dx4e N3gx4e S3c-4d S4g-4f P6d-6e {~ The classic counter pawn push. The whole board will now be the battleground.  ~} P6fx6e N7cx6e S7g-6f P8e-8f P8gx8f {~ Interestingly enough
column27: the same position already occured in a game between the~ same two players. In November 1988 Habu had black against (at that time) Meijin~ Tanigawa.~ ~} B4bx8f { ? ~ Almost ten years ago
column29: which is much better. After~ Px8f P2d Bx2d P3e Rx8e P*8h white had a good position and went on to win the~ game from there.~ ~} B6hx8f R8bx8f P2e-2d P2cx2d P'2c {~ A severe attack. If Kx2c then P*2e Px2e P*2d Kx2d B*4a and the attack only~ becomes stronger. Taking with the gold is also not very attractive. In the~ analysing room some people already wondered if the game was over. However
column30: ~ even at this level the game is never that simple...~ ~} G3bx2c S6fx6e P'6f G6g-7g R8f-8e N'1e {~ This knight drop is always a problem if the pawn is not pushed to 1d. !  However
column31: ~ also good seems 63.P*2e Px2e Rx2e P*2d Sx5d (Sx5d N3c+ and Rx8e). ~ ~} S4dx4e B'4a B'3b {! ~ A great fighting move and the only defense that keeps Habu's position together~ (at least for the time being).~ ~} B4ax6c+ N'6g G7gx6g P6fx6g+ G7hx6g R8ex6e S'4a {?? ~ A horrible mistake. Tanigawa: 'I thought I was threatening an easy mate
column32: but~ after having dropped the silver I realised that it wasn't mate at all'.~ ~} R6ex6c {?? ~ Habu is victim to the same illusion. Both players had plenty of time here~ (Tanigawa 25 minutes and Habu more than 90 minutes). Actually Habu took 15~ minutes to play this move. His shallow analysis: Sx3b+ Kx3b B*4a K3a N*2c~ and a quick mate. However
column33: after N*2c K2b G*3b K1b Nx1a+ Kx1a G2b Kx2b Rx2d~ K3a there is no mate. There are actually quite a few variations that seem to~ lead to mate in this position
column35: Sx3b+ Kx3b Nx2c+~ Kx2c N*1e K3c B*2b K3b and no mate. Conclusion: if Habu would have played~ 74.Rx6g+ instead of !Rx!6c
column36: he would have won the game!~ ~} S4ax3b+ K2bx3b N1ex2c+ K3b-4a P'6d R6cx6d P'6e R6dx6e P'6f R6e-8e B'6c S'5b B6cx7d+ R8e-8g+ {~ Habu: 'G*6i might have been better.. '. However
column37: even if 88.G*6i then K7h~ B*8g K8h is no mate and black wins.'~ ~} G6g-7g S'8h { ~ Nothing helps. For example 90.G*6i Kx6i +Rx8i G*7i B*4g G*5h and black wins.~ ~} R2hx8h G'6i K7ix6i +R8gx8h S'3b K4a-5a +B7dx5b K5ax5b S3bx4c {~ Resigns~ ~ Not an easy mate. Habu took three minutes before resigning to confirm the variations:~ a) 100.Kx4c N*5e Px5e G*4d Kx4d Sx5e and easy mate~ b) 100.K6a S5b= (S5b+ is also good) Kx5b G*5c Kx5c N*6e and mate~ c) 100.K6b N*7d K6c G*7c Kx7c S*6b and mate~ ~ A hard blow to Habu who not only lost but also had his endgame confidence~ shaken. Let's see how he recovers in the second game on April 26th and 27th.~ ~ }"

column22: after which white has almost~no choice but to play Furibisha (Ranging Rook). This was what Tanigawa~had planned for this game. The differences are very subtle
column23: and it is hard~to say if they have any influence on the outcome of the game. Sanada ignores~this reasoning and plays the opening differently.~} S3a-4b P5g-5f P5c-5d P3g-3f G4a-3b {After considerable thought

column25: if he can keep~the bishop on 7i
column26: since this bishop does not have to go anywhere to let~the king enter the castle. The opening strategy of both players is now a~debate between white not having pushed the rook pawn while black has moved~this pawn (one move loss for black perhaps) and the quick black castle against~the normal white castle (one move win for black).~} P7c-7d K6h-7h P7d-7e {Difficult to judge. White plays this to get a pawn in hand
column27: and also gets the~black bishop to move

column32: but this gives Tanigawa the opportunity~to improve his position.~} P9d-9e {This move (which was also the sealed move) will make an important difference~later.~} S7g-8f B7e-5c R2h-7h P4d-4e B4f-2h P3d-3e P5f-5e P5dx5e P3fx3e P8c-8d B2hx5e P8d-8e S8fx8e B5c-6d B5ex6d P6cx6d P2e-2d S3cx2d S8e-7d B'9d {A painful drop

column35: but this is a big mistake that gives~Sanada the opportunity to turn around the game. After 33...P*7d 34.Sx7d P*7c 35.S8e and~only then Gx5g
column36: white has no chance to promote the rook and get counterplay~for losing two generals to the bishop.~} B'6a {Strong counter.~} P'5d {Looks weak
column37: but is actually white's best chance. Tanigawa thought long and hard~about attacking possibilities like 34...P*8f 35.Px8f Rx8e 36.Px8e S*8f
column38: but after~B*7f  white loses because of the double threat on 4c. To kill this and a~possible bishopdrop on 5e
column39: Tanigawa defends.~} B6ax4c+ G3bx4c B'6a S'3b B6ax4c+ {Sanada for a moment switches roles with 'Lightning Speed Endgame' Tanigawa
column40: but~fails. 37.G*8c kills the rook and is the way to go in this position. Black will~win after this
column41: but still has to play a long and careful game. Sanada thinks~he has found a forced win
column42: but he has overlooked a move.~} S3bx4c G'4b K2b-3c G4bx4c K3cx4c S'3d K4c-5b P'5c K5bx5c G'4c K5c-6c S8e-7d K6c-7b G4c-5b {So far a forced sequence. Sanada intended to play 44.P*7c
column43: which seems~winning after 44...Nx7c 45.G5b and 44...Sx7c 45.Sx7c+ Nx7c 46.P*7d. However
column44: Sanada here~realised that in the last variation after P*7d
column45: white has the brilliant rook~sacrifice Rx8g+. Then
column46: after Kx8g P*8f Kx8f P*8e Rx8e G*7f Kx7f B*6g K8g Bx8e+~black loses the rook
column47: his mating threat and the game. After 44.G5b black's~attack is not strong enough.~} B'8d G5bx6b K7bx6b S'7c B8dx7c S7dx7c+ N8ax7c B'5a K6bx5a R7ex7c+ G'7b +R7cx8b G7bx8b R'7a K5a-6b R7ax9a+ G'8a +R9a-9d B'6g {With some good defending
column48: Tanigawa has killed black's attacking chances and~now goes for the black king himself. There is no defense...~} +R9dx6d P'6c N'7d K6b-7b N7dx8b+ G8ax8b L'7i P'7c {Resigns            0/479        0/466~Time:              07:59:00     07:46:00~~A brave effort by Sanada
column49: but he now faces the huge task of winning all~remaining games. Next game on November 18th and 19th.~}"

column20: "P7g-7f P8c-8d G6i-7h G4a-3b S7i-6h P3c-3d B8h-7g {In the first game of this match
column21: it was kind of surprising to see Tanigawa~choose a Furibisha strategy. Since this is not his natural strategy
column22: he was~expected to use it only if he would get a comfortable lead in the match. This~game's opening is no surprise
column23: though. Tanigawa is a specialist in the~Kakugawari (Bishop Exchange) opening.~} P8d-8e S3i-3h S7a-7b P2g-2f B2bx7g+ S6hx7g S3a-4b P1g-1f P1c-1d P9g-9f P9c-9d P4g-4f P6c-6d S3h-4g S7b-6c K5i-6h G6a-5b S4g-5f S4b-3c G4i-5h K5a-4b K6h-7i S6c-5d P6g-6f P7c-7d P4f-4e {Aggresive
column24: Tanigawa-like opening play. Since white has not played the 4d pawn
column25: ~black takes control of the center. White's position is very strong
column26: though and~hard to break down.~} N8a-7c P3g-3f K4b-3a N2i-3g R8b-6b B'4f {Strong square to drop the bishop. It seems Sanada had nothing special against~Tanigawa's strategy and is forced into a waiting game (sakusen-make).~} R6b-6a K7i-8h L9a-9b {Criticized by Morishita
column27: whi felt that immediately 21...S6c followed by P5d~would have been better.~} R2h-4h G5b-4b {All waiting moves by white. He can only be patient until black starts the~attack.~} L1i-1g {Tanigawa decides that attacking on the edge is more promising than attacking~through the center.~} S5d-6c {The sealed move and a subtle defense move. 23...K2b is not so good
column28: because of~24.N2e S2d 25.S5e which favours black.~} S5f-4g {Another preparation move
column29: this time to defend the head of the knight against~a later pawn drop on 3f.~} P5c-5d R4h-1h S3c-2d P2f-2e S2d-3c P1f-1e P1dx1e L1gx1e L1ax1e R1hx1e P'1c R1e-1i R6a-8a P'1b S3c-2b P3f-3e P3dx3e B4fx3e G4b-5b P4e-4d P4cx4d B3ex4d L'4b B4dx2b+ {Strong bishop sacrifice and the only way to continue the attack.~} K3ax2b {Better would have been 36...Gx2b. After 37.P1a+ Lx4g+ 38.Gx4g P8f 39.Sx8f B*5h the~position can go either way.~} P1b-1a+ K2bx1a P2e-2d {If Tanigawa would have played 38.P*3c Gx3c 39.P*1d Px1d 40.Rx1d P*1c 41.P*3d G3b 42.S*3c~Nx3c 43.Px3c+ Gx3c 44.L*3f he would have won quickly. 'I should have looked at that~more carefully' -Tanigawa. Now Sanada gets chances to get back in the game.~} K1a-2b P2dx2c+ G3bx2c P'2d G2cx2d L'2h P'2c L2hx2d P2cx2d S'3d P'3c {Strong defense. After this
column30: black is struggling to make his attack work.~} G'2c K2b-3a S3dx3c+ K3a-4a P'4c L4bx4c +S3cx4c G5bx4c P'4d G4cx4d L'4f K4a-5b L4fx4d B'5e {Great move
column31: but at the wrong time. If white would have played 100.P8f first
column32: ~the outcome of the game would have been very doubtful after 51.Sx8f (Px8f~P*8e is very difficult to defend) B*5e 52.L4b+ Kx4b 53.N4e S*4d 54.R3i P*3h 55.Rx3h P*3g.~} L4d-4b+ K5b-6b {The difference with the variation above is that with the silver still~defending the pawn on 6f
column33: black can win the bishop by P5f and wins
column34: so~white can not take the lance here.~} S4g-4f {Great silver sacrifice adding decisive strength to black's attack.~} B5ex4f R1i-4i B4f-3e R4i-4c+ P8e-8f S7gx8f L'8d P'4d L8dx8f P8gx8f S'6i G'5c K6b-7a G5cx6c {It is close
column35: but white has no mate and no defense.~} R8ax8f P'8g S6ix7h+ K8hx7h R8fx8g+ K7hx8g B'6i S'7h P'8f K8gx8f S'8e K8f-7g S8ex7f K7g-6h"

"P7g-7f P8c-8d S7i-6h P3c-3d P6g-6f S7a-6b P5g-5f P5c-5d S3i-4h S3a-4b {Both players are experts in the Yagura
column21: especially Sato who has written a~number of very good books on this extremely complicated strategy. This double~Yagura was therefore expected. However
column22: white's results have not been good~recently and it was interesting to see what Sato would play.~} G4i-5h G4a-3b G6i-7h K5a-4a K5i-6i P7c-7d G5h-6g S6b-5c P2g-2f P8d-8e S6h-7g S5c-6d {This quick attacking strategy must have surprised Habu. It is not really Sato's~style to attack this early. At professional level
column23: it is a major gamble to~attack without the king being safe. Sato: 'If I would be white I thought I had~to go for it'. We are still before lunch on the first day of a two day game.~Having already such a complicated position is very rare.~} P2f-2e P7d-7e P6f-6e P7ex7f G6gx7f {Habu took only one minute for this move
column24: but it took Sato completely by~surprise. 'I had only thought about 27.Sx7f and 27.Px6d'. Usually it is not~a good place for the gold to be on 7f
column25: but Habu is aiming at putting pressure~on the left side of the position.~} S6d-5c B8h-7i R8b-7b P'7e S5c-4d S4h-5g P5d-5e P5fx5e S4dx5e P'5f S5e-4d P2e-2d P2cx2d R2hx2d P'2c R2d-2h S4b-5c G7h-6g S5c-5d K6i-7h P1c-1d P9g-9f G6a-5a {Not good. Pushing the pawn in front of the king is usually the last thing one~wants to do
column26: but Habu judges that white's pieces have all gone to the right~side of the board
column27: while his pieces are all on the left side. There he wants~to attack. Habu's strategic brilliance is clear from this game.~} P8ex8f S7gx8f R7b-5b P'8d P'5e P8d-8c+ P5ex5f S5g-6h S4d-5e {Better 31...S4d-4e to open the bishop diagonal. column28: after 32.S8f-7g S5e 33.P7d P*7e 34.Gx7e~P5g+ 35.Gx5g S4e-5f 36.P7c+ Habu still seems to be winning.~} P7e-7d P5f-5g+ {No choice. If white defends with 32...P*7b to aim for the same position as in~the comments above
column29: black plays 33.S7e S5e 34.G6g-7g which is much better for~black. It is interesting that in this game control of the board is more~important than the position of the king. Habu's king is obviously not in the~perfect castle shape
column30: but because he controls the left side of the board
column31: ~Sato has no chance to attack. Habu's comments: 'This Shogi looks like Go
column32: ~doesn't it'.~} G6gx5g S5e-5f G5gx5f B2bx9i+ S'8h {Subtle move that decides the game. If black plays 35.+B8h immediately
column34: which leaves all the black generals~undefended or 35...+Bx8i 36.Kx8i L*8g which is also nasty.~} +B9i-9h S8h-8g +B9h-9i B7i-8h +B9ix8h K7hx8h {The difference with the bishop exchange in the variation before is clear. column35: but I do not think Habu has lost a winning endgame~position since he was three years old.~} L'2f P'2g S5d-4e G5fx4e L2fx2g+ R2hx2g R5b-5h+ B'7g P'8e S8f-7e P'5f L'5i +R5hx4g G4ex3d B'4e R2g-2h B4ex3d B7gx1a+ P5f-5g+ L5ix5g P'5f L'3f P5fx5g+ L3fx3d +P5gx6h L3dx3b+ G4bx3b R2hx6h L'8f S7ex8f P8ex8f G7fx8f P'8e L'5d P8ex8f S'5b {Time:              07:32:00     07:47:00~~A surprisingly one-sided game between these two. Still
column37: since~Sato will have black in game two. That game he has to win.~}"
